\section*{ğŸ›°ï¸ Space-Based Internet}

Space-based internet uses satellite constellations in Low Earth Orbit (LEO) to deliver global connectivity. 

It aims to provide high-speed, low-latency internet access to remote and underserved areas. 

Operates without ground cables, relying on satellites that act as wireless routers in space. 

\textbf{Data transmission path:} User antenna $\rightarrow$ Satellite $\rightarrow$ Satellite $\rightarrow$ Ground hub. 

Signals travel in milliseconds through laser inter-satellite links (ISLs) and ground stations.

\subsection*{Major Projects}
\begin{itemize}
    \item Starlink (SpaceX)
    \item OneWeb
    \item Amazonâ€™s Project Kuiper
\end{itemize}

\subsection*{Benefits}
\begin{itemize}
    \item Provides coverage to rural, oceanic, and disaster-affected regions.
    \item Enables education, healthcare, and communication in remote zones.
    \item Reduces dependence on fiber-optic infrastructure.
\end{itemize}

\subsection*{Challenges}
\begin{itemize}
    \item Orbital congestion and space debris risk.
    \item High operational cost and maintenance.
    \item Signal interference and regulatory issues.
\end{itemize}

\textbf{Impact:} Aims to make global internet access universal, turning connectivity into a basic human right rather than a luxury.

\section*{ğŸŒ Space Networks (TDRS \& LCRD)}

\subsection*{ğŸ”¸ TDRS â€“ Tracking and Data Relay Satellite System}
Developed and operated by NASA.

A network of geostationary satellites providing real-time communication between spacecraft and Earth.

Ensures continuous coverage for spacecraft like the ISS, Hubble Space Telescope, and other low-orbit missions.

\textbf{Data relay path:} Spacecraft $\rightarrow$ TDRS satellite $\rightarrow$ Ground terminal.

Eliminates the need for spacecraft to wait for direct line-of-sight passes.

Handles telemetry, tracking, command, and data transmission.

Positioned about 35,786 km above Earth in geostationary orbit (GEO).

\subsection*{ğŸ”¸ LCRD â€“ Laser Communications Relay Demonstration}
A NASA mission testing laser (optical) communication in space.

Uses laser light instead of radio waves to transmit data.

Offers up to 100$\times$ faster data rates compared to traditional RF systems.

Provides smaller antennas, lower interference, and higher security.

Demonstrates how future missions can send high-resolution data, images, and videos more efficiently.

Helps prepare for deep-space communication systems using optical links.

Combined with TDRS, LCRD represents the evolution toward a high-speed space communication network.

\section*{ğŸŒŒ Artificial Gravity \& Microgravity}

\subsection*{ğŸ”¸ Microgravity Effects}
In space, astronauts experience microgravity (near weightlessness).

Long exposure causes:
\begin{itemize}
    \item Muscle atrophy (loss of strength)
    \item Bone density reduction
    \item Cardiovascular weakening
    \item Fluid redistribution affecting vision and balance
    \item Disorientation and sleep difficulties
\end{itemize}

These effects pose serious risks for long-duration missions (e.g., Mars).

\subsection*{ğŸ”¸ Artificial Gravity Concept}

Artificial gravity is produced by centrifugal force from rotation â€” not real gravity, but an equivalent effect.

\[
a = \omega^2 \times r
\]

\textbf{Where:}
\begin{align*}
a & = \text{artificial gravity} \\
\omega & = \text{angular velocity (rotation speed)} \\
r & = \text{radius of rotation}
\end{align*}

Increasing radius allows slower, more comfortable rotation.

Too-fast rotation causes Coriolis effects (dizziness or nausea).

\subsection*{ğŸ”¸ Design Methods}
\begin{itemize}
    \item \textbf{Rotating spacecraft:} The entire spacecraft spins slowly.
    \item \textbf{Centrifugal habitats:} Only a ring or section spins to generate gravity.
    \item \textbf{Tethered systems:} Two modules connected by a cable rotate around a center of mass.
\end{itemize}

\subsection*{ğŸ”¸ Research \& Development}

NASA, ESA, and JAXA are experimenting with small centrifuges to simulate artificial gravity.

JAXAâ€™s Kibo module aboard the ISS studies partial gravity on biological organisms.

Stanford Torus and Oâ€™Neill Cylinder are classic theoretical models for rotating space habitats.

The Lunar Gateway and future Mars missions may integrate artificial gravity modules.

\subsection*{ğŸ”¸ Challenges}
\begin{itemize}
    \item Structural stress from constant rotation.
    \item High energy demand for spin-up and stabilization.
    \item Maintaining balance and orientation control.
    \item Human adaptation to partial or rotating gravity.
\end{itemize}

\subsection*{ğŸ”¸ Future Outlook}
Artificial gravity is essential for long-term human survival in space.

It enables healthier, more sustainable missions to Mars and beyond.

It represents a major step toward building livable habitats beyond Earth.

